{"parentUuid":"1b92b5c5-6f82-4612-94b4-369d058bb6bd","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_011ciYZVzH8zSg8kxjCt2jTw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is the \"11-20 money request game\" - a well-known game theory problem studied by Arad and Rubinstein (2012). Let me think about what human participants actually do in this game.\n\nIn this game:\n- Each player picks a number between 11 and 20\n- Each player receives the number they pick (in shekels)\n- If a player picks exactly 1 less than the other player, they get a bonus of 20 shekels\n\nSo if I pick 19 and you pick 20, I get 19+20=39, you get 20.\nIf we both pick 20, we each get 20.\n\n\nIf I pick 18 and you pick 20, I get 18, you get 20.\n\nThe Nash equilibrium gets interesting here - there's this iterated dominance chain where choosing 20 seems safest, but then someone could undercut with 19 to grab that bonus, which then incentivizes choosing 18, and so on. But empirically, when Arad and Rubinstein studied actual human behavior, most people cluster around 20 with a significant secondary group choosing 19, suggesting people balance the guaranteed payoff against the temptation of the bonus.\n\nLooking at the actual experimental distribution, about 35-40% of participants chose 20, roughly 25-30% chose 19, and then it drops off with smaller percentages choosing 18 and below, with some scattered choices at lower numbers.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":13116,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CZDEApRtkmUnSSkMLDQSN","type":"assistant","uuid":"b6b5601b-069c-4f7e-a6fe-e3d06b9c398b","timestamp":"2026-03-19T22:28:44.073Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"/tmp/experiment",